llm_answer:
At constant pressure, the heat supplied to an ideal gas is related to its molar heat capacity by  

q = n\,C_{p,m}\,\Delta T

Solve for the molar heat capacity C_{p,m}:

C_{p,m} = \frac{q}{n\,\Delta T}

Insert the given data (q = 229 J, n = 3.0 mol, ΔT = 2.55 K):

C_{p,m} = \frac{229\ \text{J}}{(3.0\ \text{mol})(2.55\ \text{K})}
        = \frac{229}{7.65}\ \text{J K}^{-1}\text{mol}^{-1}
        ≈ 29.9\ \text{J K}^{-1}\text{mol}^{-1}

