llm_answer:
Heat supplied at constant pressure relates to the molar heat capacity at constant pressure by  
q_p = n \, C_{p,m} \, \Delta T

Solve for C_{p,m}:  
C_{p,m} = \dfrac{q_p}{n\,\Delta T}
          = \dfrac{229\;\text{J}}{(3.0\;\text{mol})(2.55\;\text{K})}
          = 29.9\;\text{J K}^{-1}\text{ mol}^{-1}

For an ideal gas, the relationship between the molar heat capacities is  
C_{p,m} = C_{v,m} + R

Hence  
C_{v,m} = C_{p,m} - R
          = 29.9 - 8.314
          = 21.6\;\text{J K}^{-1}\text{ mol}^{-1}

\boxed{21.6} J K^{-1} mol^{-1}

