llm_answer:
The compression (compressibility) factor is defined as

\[
Z=\frac{P\bar V}{RT}
\]

1.  Obtain the molar volume from the density.  

   Mass density: ρ = 133.2 kg m⁻³  
   Molar mass: M = 18.02 g mol⁻¹ = 0.01802 kg mol⁻¹  

   \[
   \bar V=\frac{M}{\rho}=\frac{0.01802\ \text{kg mol}^{-1}}{133.2\ \text{kg m}^{-3}}
          =1.353\times10^{-4}\ \text{m}^3\text{ mol}^{-1}
          =0.1353\ \text{L mol}^{-1}
   \]

2.  Insert the data in the definition of Z.  
   Pressure: P = 327.6 atm  
   Temperature: T = 776.4 K  
   Gas constant: R = 0.082057 L atm mol⁻¹ K⁻¹  

   \[
   Z=\frac{(327.6\ \text{atm})(0.1353\ \text{L mol}^{-1})}
           {(0.082057\ \text{L atm mol}^{-1}\text{K}^{-1})(776.4\ \text{K})}
     =\frac{44.32}{63.71}
     =0.696
   \]

Hence, the compression factor under the stated conditions is

\[
\boxed{0.696}
\]

