Given  

h = 6.626\,070\,15 \times 10^{-34}\ \mathrm{J\,s}  
m_e = 9.109\,383\,56 \times 10^{-31}\ \mathrm{kg}  
K = 100\ \mathrm{eV} = 100 \times 1.602\,176\,634 \times 10^{-19}\ \mathrm{J}
   = 1.602\,176\,634 \times 10^{-17}\ \mathrm{J}

Step 1:  Compute 2 m_e K  
2m_eK = 2(9.109\,383\,56 \times 10^{-31})(1.602\,176\,634 \times 10^{-17})  
       = 2.919\,778 \times 10^{-47}\ \mathrm{kg^2\,m^2\,s^{-2}}

Step 2:  Take the square root  
\sqrt{2m_eK} = \sqrt{2.919\,778 \times 10^{-47}}
             = 5.401 \times 10^{-24}\ \mathrm{kg^{1/2}\,m\,s^{-1}}

Step 3:  Apply the de Broglie relation  
\lambda = \frac{h}{\sqrt{2m_eK}}
        = \frac{6.626\,070\,15 \times 10^{-34}}
               {5.401 \times 10^{-24}}
        = 1.227 \times 10^{-10}\ \mathrm{m}

Step 4:  Convert meters to nanometers (1 nm = 10^{-9} m)  
\lambda = 0.1227 \ \mathrm{nm}

Rounded to three significant figures:

\boxed{0.123} nm

