question:
$$
\text {Calculate the energy of a photon for a wavelength of } 100 \mathrm{pm} \text { (about one atomic diameter). }
$$

llm_answer:
First convert every quantity in the expression  

\[
\beta = 2\pi c\tilde{\omega}_{\text{obs}}\left(\frac{\mu}{2D}\right)^{1/2}
\]

to SI units (per molecule).

1. Reduced mass of H\textsuperscript{35}Cl  

   Atomic masses  
   m\textsubscript{H}=1.007825 u,\;
   m\textsubscript{Cl}=34.968853 u,  
   1 u = 1.660 54 × 10^{-27} kg

   \[
   \mu \;=\;\frac{m_{\text{H}}m_{\text{Cl}}}{m_{\text{H}}+m_{\text{Cl}}}
        =0.97959\;\text{u}=1.62665\times10^{-27}\,\text{kg}
   \]

2. Dissociation energy per molecule  

   \[
   D=\frac{440.2\times10^{3}\ \text{J mol}^{-1}}{N_{A}}
      =7.3097\times10^{-19}\ \text{J}
   \]
   hence   2D = 1.46194 × 10^{-18} J.

3. Square-root factor  

   \[
   \left(\frac{\mu}{2D}\right)^{1/2}
      =\left(\frac{1.62665\times10^{-27}}{1.46194\times10^{-18}}\right)^{1/2}
      =3.3354\times10^{-5}\ \text{s\,m}^{-1}
   \]

4. Angular frequency factor  

   \[
   2\pi c\tilde{\omega}_{\text{obs}}
      =2\pi(2.997\,924\,58\times10^{8}\,\text{m s}^{-1})
           (2886\,\text{cm}^{-1}\times100\,\text{m cm}^{-1})
      =5.4362\times10^{14}\ \text{s}^{-1}
   \]

5. β value  

   \[
   \beta=(5.4362\times10^{14})(3.3354\times10^{-5})
         =1.813\times10^{10}\ \text{m}^{-1}
   \]

Rounded to three significant figures,

\[
\boxed{1.81}\;10^{10}\,\text{m}^{-1}
\]

