llm_answer:
Step 1 – Average kinetic energy of a thermal neutron in one dimension  
Equipartition gives ½ k_{B} T per quadratic degree of freedom.  
In one dimension  

E_{kin}= \frac{1}{2}k_{B}T = \frac{p^{2}}{2m_{n}}  

Step 2 – Momentum corresponding to this energy  

p = \sqrt{m_{n}k_{B}T}  

Step 3 – de Broglie wavelength  

\lambda = \frac{h}{p}= \frac{h}{\sqrt{m_{n}k_{B}T}}  

Step 4 – Insert constants  

h = 6.626\,070\,15\times10^{-34}\,\text{J·s}  
k_{B}=1.380\,649\times10^{-23}\,\text{J K}^{-1}  
m_{n}=1.674\,927\,498\times10^{-27}\,\text{kg}  
T = 373 K  

\lambda=\frac{6.626\,070\,15\times10^{-34}}
          {\sqrt{(1.674\,927\,498\times10^{-27})(1.380\,649\times10^{-23})(373)}}  

\lambda\simeq 2.26\times10^{-10}\ \text{m}  

Step 5 – Convert to picometres (1 pm = 10^{-12} m)  

\lambda \simeq 2.26\times10^{-10}\,\text{m}=2.26\times10^{2}\,\text{pm}  

\boxed{2.26\times 10^{2}} pm

