The magnitudes of the two forces at the same separation r are  

Electric: F_e = k_e \dfrac{e^{2}}{r^{2}}  
Gravitational: F_g = G \dfrac{m_p m_e}{r^{2}}

Their ratio is independent of r:

\displaystyle
\frac{F_e}{F_g}= \frac{k_e\,e^{2}}{G\,m_p\,m_e}

Insert the CODATA values  

k_e = 8.987\,551\,787\times10^{9}\;\text{N·m}^{2}\text{/C}^{2}  
e   = 1.602\,176\,634\times10^{-19}\;\text{C}  
G   = 6.674\,30\times10^{-11}\;\text{N·m}^{2}\text{/kg}^{2}  
m_p = 1.672\,621\,923\,69\times10^{-27}\;\text{kg}  
m_e = 9.109\,383\,7015\times10^{-31}\;\text{kg}

1.  Numerator  
   k_e e^{2}= (8.987\,551\,787\times10^{9})\,(1.602\,176\,634\times10^{-19})^{2}  
   = 2.30\times10^{-28}

2.  Denominator  
   G m_p m_e = (6.674\,30\times10^{-11})(1.672\,621\,923\,69\times10^{-27})(9.109\,383\,7015\times10^{-31})  
   = 1.02\times10^{-67}

3.  Ratio  
   \dfrac{F_e}{F_g}= \dfrac{2.30\times10^{-28}}{1.02\times10^{-67}}
   \approx 2.27\times10^{39}

Hence, the electrical force between a proton and an electron is about 2.27×10^{39} times stronger than their gravitational attraction.

\[
\boxed{2.27}\,10^{39}
\]

