llm_answer:
Step 1 – Determine the dissolved CO₂ concentration  
For the physiological bicarbonate buffer the Henderson–Hasselbalch relation at 37 °C is  

pH = pK′a  +  log([HCO₃⁻]/[CO₂(dissolved)]) ,  pK′a ≈ 6.10  

Solve for [CO₂]:  

[CO₂] = [HCO₃⁻] / 10^{\,\text{pH} - \text{pK′a}}
       = 15\;\text{mM}/10^{7.40-6.10}
       = 15\;\text{mM}/10^{1.30}
       ≈ 15\;\text{mM}/19.95
       ≈ 0.75\;\text{mM}

Step 2 – Determine the H₂CO₃ concentration  
Dissolved CO₂ and true carbonic acid are rapidly inter-convertible:

CO₂(dissolved) + H₂O ⇌ H₂CO₃  K_h = [H₂CO₃]/[CO₂] ≈ 1.7 × 10⁻³ (37 °C)

[H₂CO₃] = K_h [CO₂] = (1.7 × 10⁻³)(0.75 \text{mM}) ≈ 1.3 × 10⁻³ \text{mM}

Step 3 – New pH when [CO₂] rises to 3 mM  
Keeping [HCO₃⁻] = 15 mM:

pH_{new} = 6.10 + log(15/3) = 6.10 + log(5) ≈ 6.10 + 0.70 = 6.80

Final numerical answers

[H₂CO₃] = \boxed{1.3\times10^{-3}}\text{ mM}

[CO₂\,(dissolved)] = \boxed{0.75}\text{ mM}

pH_{\,\text{new}} = \boxed{6.80}

