llm_answer:
The transition–state theory expression for a unimolecular rate constant is  

k = (k_B T / h)\,e^{-\Delta G^{\ddagger}/RT}

Because the temperature and the pre-exponential factor (k_B T / h) are identical for the catalyzed (cat) and uncatalyzed (uncat) reactions, taking the ratio of the two rate constants eliminates this common factor:

\frac{k_{\text{cat}}}{k_{\text{uncat}}}=e^{-(\Delta G^{\ddagger}_{\text{cat}}-\Delta G^{\ddagger}_{\text{uncat}})/RT}
        =e^{(\Delta G^{\ddagger}_{\text{uncat}}-\Delta G^{\ddagger}_{\text{cat}})/RT}

Hence

\Delta\Delta G^{\ddagger}
      =\Delta G^{\ddagger}_{\text{uncat}}-\Delta G^{\ddagger}_{\text{cat}}
      =RT\ln\!\left(\frac{k_{\text{cat}}}{k_{\text{uncat}}}\right)

Insert the given data (T = 25 °C = 298 K, R = 8.314 J mol⁻¹ K⁻¹ = 0.008314 kJ mol⁻¹ K⁻¹):

RT = 0.008314\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}\text{K}^{-1}\times 298\;\text{K}=2.48\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}

\ln\!\left(\frac{k_{\text{cat}}}{k_{\text{uncat}}}\right)
   =\ln\!\left(\frac{14\;\text{s}^{-1}}{1\times10^{-15}\;\text{s}^{-1}}\right)
   =\ln\!\left(1.4\times10^{16}\right)
   =\ln(1.4)+16\ln(10)
   \approx 0.336+16(2.303)=37.18

Finally,

\Delta\Delta G^{\ddagger}= (2.48\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1})(37.18)\approx 92\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}

\[
\boxed{92} \text{ kJ/mol}
\]

