llm_answer:
Let  

Cu²⁺ + 4 NH₃ ⇌ [Cu(NH₃)₄]²⁺ , β₄ = K_{stable}^{\ominus}=2.1\times10^{13}

1. Define x = equilibrium concentration of free Cu²⁺.

2. Material balances (initial → equilibrium)

 [Cu²⁺]     : 0.20 → x  
 [NH₃]      : 1.0  → 1.0 – 4(0.20 – x)=0.20+4x  
 [Cu(NH₃)₄²⁺]: 0   → 0.20 – x

3. Apply β₄:

 β₄ = \dfrac{[Cu(NH₃)₄²⁺]}{[Cu²⁺][NH₃]⁴}  
 2.1\times10^{13} = \dfrac{0.20-x}{x\,(0.20+4x)^{4}}

4. Because β₄ is enormous, x ≪ 0.20, thus 0.20–x ≈ 0.20 and 0.20+4x ≈ 0.20:

 2.1\times10^{13} ≈ \dfrac{0.20}{x\,(0.20)^{4}}

 (0.20)^{4}=0.0016 ⟹ \dfrac{0.20}{x\,(0.0016)}=2.1\times10^{13}

 \dfrac{0.20}{0.0016}=125 ⇒ \frac{125}{x}=2.1\times10^{13}

 x = \dfrac{125}{2.1\times10^{13}} = 5.95\times10^{-12}

5. Residual concentration of Cu²⁺:

\[
\boxed{6.0\times10^{-12}}\ \text{mol dm}^{-3}
\]

