llm_answer:
Step 1 : Convert the pH of the salt solution to the hydroxide-ion concentration.  
pH = 9  ⇒ pOH = 14 − 9 = 5  
[OH⁻] = 10^{−5}\ \text{mol dm}^{-3}

(The contribution of 10^{−7}\ \text{mol dm}^{-3} from pure water is two orders of magnitude smaller and will be taken into account in the final numerical evaluation.)

Step 2 : Write the hydrolysis equilibrium of the anion X⁻ (conjugate base of the weak acid HX).

X⁻ + H₂O ⇌ HX + OH⁻

Initial concentrations (in mol dm^{-3})  
[X⁻]₀ = 0.200, [HX]₀ = 0, [OH⁻]₀ = 10^{−7}

Let x be the amount of X⁻ that hydrolyses:

Equilibrium concentrations  
[X⁻] = 0.200 − x  
[HX] = x  
[OH⁻] = 10^{−7} + x

The measured pH tells us that at equilibrium  
10^{−7} + x = 10^{−5}  ⇒ x = 10^{−5} − 10^{−7} ≈ 9.9 × 10^{−6}

Step 3 : Evaluate the base-dissociation (hydrolysis) constant K_b of X⁻.

K_b = ([HX][OH⁻])/[X⁻]  
  = \dfrac{x(10^{−7}+x)}{0.200-x}  
  = \dfrac{(9.9\times10^{−6})(1.0\times10^{−5})}{0.200}  
  ≈ 5.0\times10^{−10}

Step 4 : Convert K_b to the acid-dissociation constant K_a of HX using K_w = 1.0 × 10^{−14} (25 °C).

K_a = K_w / K_b  
  = \dfrac{1.0\times10^{−14}}{5.0\times10^{−10}}  
  = 2.0\times10^{−5}

Hence, the dissociation equilibrium constant of the weak acid HX is

\boxed{2.0 \times 10^{-5}}

