llm_answer:
Step 1 – Initial composition (pH = 7.40)

[H⁺]₀ = 10^{-7.40}=3.98\times10^{-8}\,\text{M}

K_{\mathrm a1}=4.5\times10^{-7},\;K_{\mathrm a2}=4.7\times10^{-11}

[H_2CO_3]_0=\dfrac{[H⁺]_0[HCO_3^-]_0}{K_{\mathrm a1}}
            =\dfrac{(3.98\times10^{-8})(0.022)}{4.5\times10^{-7}}
            =1.95\times10^{-3}\,\text{M}

[CO_3^{2-}]_0=\dfrac{K_{\mathrm a2}[HCO_3^-]_0}{[H⁺]_0}
             =\dfrac{(4.7\times10^{-11})(0.022)}{3.98\times10^{-8}}
             =2.60\times10^{-5}\,\text{M}

Total dissolved inorganic carbon  
C_T=[H_2CO_3]+[HCO_3^-]+[CO_3^{2-}]
    =1.95\times10^{-3}+0.02200+2.60\times10^{-5}
    =2.397\times10^{-2}\,\text{M}

Charge balance at the start fixes the (spectator) cation concentration, called [Na⁺]:
[Na⁺]_0=[HCO_3^-]_0+2[CO_3^{2-}]_0+[OH⁻]_0-[H⁺]_0
        =0.02200+2(2.60\times10^{-5})+2.51\times10^{-7}-3.98\times10^{-8}
        =2.205\times10^{-2}\,\text{M}

Step 2 – Final carbonate composition (pH = 7.00)

[H⁺]_f=10^{-7}=1.0\times10^{-7}\,\text{M}

From K_{\mathrm a1}:  \dfrac{[HCO_3^-]}{[H_2CO_3]}=\dfrac{K_{\mathrm a1}}{[H⁺]_f}=4.5  
From K_{\mathrm a2}:  \dfrac{[CO_3^{2-}]}{[HCO_3^-]}=\dfrac{K_{\mathrm a2}}{[H⁺]_f}=4.7\times10^{-4}

Let [H_2CO_3]=x.  Then  

[HCO_3^-]=4.5x,\qquad [CO_3^{2-}]=4.5x(4.7\times10^{-4})=2.115\times10^{-3}x

Using the constant total carbon C_T:

x+4.5x+2.115\times10^{-3}x=C_T

x=\dfrac{C_T}{5.502115}=4.36\times10^{-3}\,\text{M}

Hence  

[H_2CO_3]_f=4.36\times10^{-3}\,\text{M}  
[HCO_3^-]_f=1.96\times10^{-2}\,\text{M}  
[CO_3^{2-}]_f=9.22\times10^{-6}\,\text{M}

Step 3 – Charge balance after lactic acid has been added

For lactic acid   HL ⇌ H⁺ + L⁻,   K_{HL}=1.4\times10^{-4}

At pH 7.00  

\dfrac{[L^-]}{[HL]}=\dfrac{K_{HL}}{[H⁺]_f}=\dfrac{1.4\times10^{-4}}{1.0\times10^{-7}}=1.40\times10^{3}

Let L_T=[HL]+[L^-] be the total (unknown) lactate added; then  

[HL]=\dfrac{L_T}{1401},\qquad [L^-]=\dfrac{1400\,L_T}{1401}

The final charge balance is  

[Na⁺]_0+[H⁺]_f =[HCO_3^-]_f+2[CO_3^{2-}]_f+[OH⁻]_f+[L^-]

Insert the numbers:
2.205\times10^{-2}+1.0\times10^{-7}
=1.96\times10^{-2}+2(9.22\times10^{-6})+1.0\times10^{-7}+\dfrac{1400\,L_T}{1401}

Solving gives  

\dfrac{1400\,L_T}{1401}=2.424\times10^{-3}\;\text{M}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;L_T=2.426\times10^{-3}\;\text{M}

Step 4 – Amount of lactic acid that had to be added

Because no lactate was present initially, L_T is exactly the number of moles added to 1.00 dm³:

n_{\text{added}} = L_T(1.00\;\text{dm}^3)=2.43\times10^{-3}\;\text{mol}

\boxed{2.43\times10^{-3}} mol

