llm_answer:
Let  

PbS(s) ⇌ Pb^{2+} + S^{2-}   K_{sp}=3.4\times10^{-28}

s  = molar solubility = [Pb^{2+}] produced

so  K_{sp}=s\,[S^{2-}]  (1)

Because the solution is acidic ( [H_{3}O^{+}] = 3.0\times10^{-4}\;{\rm M} ), the sulphide ion is almost completely protonated:

S^{2-}+H_{3}O^{+} ⇌ HS^{-}+H_{2}O   K_{a2}=1.0\times10^{-13}

HS^{-}+H_{3}O^{+} ⇌ H_{2}S+H_{2}O  K_{a1}=8.9\times10^{-8}

For the conjugate di-acid H_{2}S the fraction of total dissolved sulfide (C_{T}=s) present as S^{2-} is  

α_{2}= \dfrac{K_{a1}K_{a2}}{[H^{+}]^{2}+K_{a1}[H^{+}]+K_{a1}K_{a2}}

Insert the numbers:

K_{a1}K_{a2}=8.9\times10^{-8}\cdot1.0\times10^{-13}=8.9\times10^{-21}  
[H^{+}]^{2}=(3.0\times10^{-4})^{2}=9.0\times10^{-8}  

α_{2}= \dfrac{8.9\times10^{-21}}{9.0\times10^{-8}} \approx 9.9\times10^{-14}

Hence  [S^{2-}]=α_{2}\,C_{T}=α_{2}s  (2)

Substituting (2) in (1):

K_{sp}=s\,(\,α_{2}s\,)=α_{2}s^{2}

s=\sqrt{\dfrac{K_{sp}}{α_{2}}}
  =\sqrt{\dfrac{3.4\times10^{-28}}{9.9\times10^{-14}}}
  \approx\sqrt{3.4\times10^{-15}}
  \approx5.9\times10^{-8}

\boxed{5.9\times10^{-8}}\ \text{M}

