llm_answer:
For a linear, rigid, homonuclear di-atomic molecule the rotational partition function in the high–temperature limit ( kT ≫ hB ) is  

q_{\mathrm{rot}} = \dfrac{8\pi^{2} I k_{\mathrm B} T}{\sigma h^{2}}

where  
σ – symmetry number ( σ = 2 for \ce{O2} )  
I – moment of inertia about the centre of mass  
h – Planck constant  
k_B – Boltzmann constant  
T – absolute temperature.  

1. Moment of inertia  
Bond length: r = 120.75\,\text{pm} = 1.2075\times10^{-10}\,\text{m}  

Mass of one \(^{16}\)O atom:  
m_O = 15.9994\,\mathrm{u} = 15.9994(1.660\,539\,066\times10^{-27})\;\text{kg}  
\;\;\;\;= 2.6568\times10^{-26}\,\text{kg}

Reduced mass:  
μ = m_O/2 = 1.3284\times10^{-26}\,\text{kg}

Moment of inertia:  
I = μr^{2} = (1.3284\times10^{-26})(1.2075\times10^{-10})^{2}  
\;\;\;\;= 1.94\times10^{-46}\,\text{kg m}^{2}

2. Evaluation of q_rot at 300 K  

q_{\mathrm{rot}} = \dfrac{8\pi^{2}(1.94\times10^{-46})(1.380\,649\times10^{-23})(300)}
                       {2(6.626\,070\,15\times10^{-34})^{2}}
               ≃ 7.24\times10^{1}

Hence, at 300 K the rotational partition function of \(\ce{O2}\) is  

\boxed{72.4}

